³ Obnoccz'os fidosque] Arbitrio suo subjectos et fideles, ut ibi timor⁷ hic amor esset obsequii caussa. Both these words denote an attach- ment to one's interest: the former, such as proceeds from fear3 in this place, that arising from Catiline's knowledge of their guilt3 and the latter, such as flows from the motive of love—M.

XV. ¹ Cum sacerdote Vestae.] The Vestal virgins, four in number, were instituted by Numa. Their office was to attend upon the rites of the goddess Vesta, the chief part whereof was the preservation of the sacred fire. If any of them proved with child, she was buried alive3 and the man who violated her honour, was thought guilty of the most wicked and heinous crime. See Kennet's Ant. B. 11.. chap. xri-M.
